::variable_semantics_01::Which statement best defines variable semantics in Java? {
~A constructor initializes a new object instance when new is used.
=Variable semantics describe what a Java variable represents and how it behaves when assigned or passed.
~Copying a reference in Java creates another pointer to the same object, not a deep copy.
~Sequencing is executing Java statements in a defined order.
}

::variable_semantics_02::Which Java construct is most directly tied to variable semantics? {
~A constructor has the same name as the class and no return type.
~Java resolves overloaded methods at compile time using argument types.
~A declaration includes a type, a name, and optionally an initializer.
=In Java, primitives copy values while object variables copy references.
}

::variable_semantics_03::Which example best demonstrates variable semantics in Java code? {
~int count = 0; is valid Java variable syntax.
~List<String> b = a; makes b and a refer to the same list instance.
=Passing an object reference to a method still allows mutation of the same object.
~Initializing a variable before using it is a basic sequencing example.
}

::variable_semantics_04::Which is a common mistake when working with variable semantics? {
~A common mistake is assuming reference assignment duplicates object contents.
~A common mistake is risking NullPointerException in long chains.
=A common mistake is assuming Java uses pass-by-reference.
~A common mistake is creating ambiguous overloads that confuse call sites.
}

::variable_semantics_05::Which test most directly validates variable semantics behavior? {
=A good test contrasts primitive parameter changes with object state changes.
~A good test verifies state before and after each modifying operation.
~A test can assert that new instances start with independent state.
~A syntax-focused test can compile snippets to confirm declarations are valid.
}

::variable_semantics_06::Which performance/maintainability statement about variable semantics is most accurate? {
=Clear variable semantics reduce confusion around side effects.
~Accidental aliasing can cause hard-to-track side effects.
~Identity matters for caching, synchronization, and aliasing behavior.
~Choosing mutable vs immutable types affects semantic clarity.
}

::variable_semantics_07::Which refactoring most improves code related to variable semantics? {
~Refactoring parameter names can reduce overuse of this.field assignments.
~Refactoring with defensive copies can prevent shared-mutable-state bugs.
=Refactoring names to reflect role (id, count, customer) improves semantic clarity.
~Refactoring equals/hashCode implementations clarifies value semantics vs identity.
}

::variable_semantics_08::Which Java API/keyword detail is most relevant to variable semantics? {
~try/finally is often used to enforce cleanup sequence.
~Optional can sometimes make nullable chain traversal safer.
~Return type alone cannot differentiate overloaded methods in Java.
=final on a reference prevents rebinding, not mutation of the referenced object.
}

::variable_semantics_09::Which debugging approach is most useful for variable semantics problems? {
~Debugging with this in watch expressions helps inspect current object state.
~Semantic bugs appear when collections rely on inconsistent equality rules.
~Inspecting identity hash codes can help confirm whether references point to the same object.
=Semantic confusion is debugged by tracking assignments and object aliases.
}

::variable_semantics_10::Which statement about variable semantics is true? {
~Readable sequencing reduces accidental order-dependent bugs.
~Java proficiency includes writing readable code that others can maintain.
~Good overloading keeps method meaning consistent across variants.
=Understanding variable semantics is essential for reasoning about Java behavior.
}
